IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
On June 20, 2023, at approximately 1934 hours, I was dispatched to a domestic disturbance involving a firearm at 1306 Pulaski Hwy in Edgewood, Maryland. I arrived on scene at approximately 1939 hours and observed a silver Dodge Ram at the exit of Extra Space Storage with a white female laying on top of the hood. While awaiting additional units, I made contact with the parties involved and ordered them to show me their hands since there was a reported firearm in the vehicle. I got an initial statement from the operator, Kimberly Dawn Nowell(2/F 01-26-1968), identified via her Maryland driver's license. Nowell, who was the caller, stated that the female on the hood of the truck was her daughter, later identified as Lauren Bohannon. Nowell stated she was helping her daughter move from her home as she'd gotten evicted today. Nowell and Bohannon had gotten into a verbal altercation that escalated as they arrived at the location. Nowell told Bohannon to exit the vehicle to go put the code in for the gate to access the storage center. Nowell stated that Bohannon exited the vehicle to do so but then began to yell at Nowell, further escalating the argument. Nowell stated that she was going to drive down to the storage unit, forcing Bohannon to walk there when Bohannon jumped on the side of her truck and began kicking and hitting the doors and windows of the truck. Nowell explained that Bohannon was able to open the driver's side door and lunged/attacked Nowell and that's when Nowell kicked Bohannon to create space between them. Nowell attempted to shut the door when Bohannon was able to regain entry and that's when Nowell brandished her firearm, threatening Bohannon with the firearm and Bohannon backed off. Nowell further explained that Bohannon had jumped back onto the truck and Nowell pressed the gas pedal, driving forward and Bohannon had fallen off the truck.

Nowell rolled around the corner, inside the complex, and called "911". Nowell came back around to the front gate and Bohannon stood in front of the truck, not allowing her to move forward as Bohannon threaten her and spat at her truck. Nowell then stated Bohannon jumped onto the hood of the truck and ripped the windshield wiper blades off of the truck. Off-duty officer 1SGT Barnes from the MDTA Police Department stopped out to assist, and I began ordering everyone out of the vehicle to separate the parties. I ordered the passenger/witness out, Brandon Eugene Baldwin(1/M 10-25-1989), and then got Bohannon off of the hood of the truck. I attempted to get a story out of Baldwin, but he was uncooperative with the investigation. I retrieve Nowell's firearm from the vehicle and secured the firearm. I identified the firearm as a Glock 43X with the serial number, BZDT639. The Glock's magazine was loaded, but a bullet was not in the chamber. I then spoke to Bohannon to get her side of the story which coincided much with her mother's, she contributed that she and had mom had gotten into a verbal altercation regarding the abuse that Bohannon had gone through during her adolescence. 

Once they arrived at the storage facility, Bohannon exited the truck but slammed the door which enraged Nowell more, causing Nowell to lock the doors and stated to Bohannon that she was leaving her at the property. That's when Bohannon got onto the side of the truck and attempted to gain entry because she did want to get left at the property. Bohannon stated that her mother told her repeatedly to get off the truck at which then Nowell opened the door, and that's when Bohannon got into Nowell's face and began screaming at her. Bohannon was kicked off the truck, and Bohannon reopened the door. Bohannon stated afterward that Nowell pointed the firearm at her, at which she asked Nowell if she was going to shoot her own daughter and Nowell replied, "Yes." Bohannon stated she got back onto the side of the truck when Nowell sped off which made her fall onto the ground. She came back around at which Bohannon jumped onto the hood of the truck, and sped to the exit of the lot.

I made the decision to place both parties involved under arrest, Bohannon and Nowell; Bohannon for Malicious Destruction of Property, possession of CDS Paraphernalia and Nowell for 1st Degree Assault, 2nd Degree Assault, and possession of a firearm in the commission of a felony. TFC Rogers transported Nowell to the barrack while I transported Bohannon. Prior to transport, I retrieved Bohannon's purse from her mother's vehicle to take with us and during a search of the purse, I discovered CDS paraphernalia as Bohannon admitted that she was a drug user. 


All seized contraband was packaged according to the Maryland State Police policy and procedure. 

Case closed via arrest.

All events occurred in Harford County, Maryland.
